entry.title: The Style Council - My Ever Changing Moods (Pop Goes New Year, 1983)
entry.content: Performing a unique version of their (at the time) unreleased song with violinist Bobby Valentino on ITV's Pop Goes New Year, 31st December 1983. Bobby is a British musician, songwriter & actor who is probably familiar to most when used as a Clark Gable lookalike in movies & tv commercials. He was an Honorary Councillor when he added violin to TSC's recording of Here's One That Got Away. Fair use claimed on this clip. entry.title: Dave Clarke - Thunder
entry.content: Dave Clarke - Thunder Taken from the EP, Red Three/3 (Deconstruction, Bush, Re-load Records 1995) | BRITISH | BEEF | Dave Clarke... Dave Clarke was born in Brighton, on 19 September 1968. He is one of the most respected (and idiosyncratic) Techno DJ's and producers of the 90's. Dave Clarke began his music career as a Hip-Hop DJ in the mid 80's, shifting to Acid House and later to Rave near the end of the decade. He began recording for Stress Records (as Pig City) in the early 90's and also appeared on R & S Records, XL Recordings and his own Magnetic North. By the mid 90's he had gradually shifted away from Rave to a brand of straightahead Techno with the ferocity of Hardcore yet the sublime feelings of classic Detroit Techno. A series of three 12's named Red 1/2/3 gained fame during 1993-96 (the last entering the Top 40 in the UK), as did his ferocious DJ sets. He's also known as a radio presenter, at the end of the year 2000 he hosted his own radio show Technology on Studio Brussels in Belgium where he promoted new Techno and Electro artists (for example Terence Fixmer). But due to recording and touring commitments the show was canceled. In September 2006 he launched a new radio show White Noise, originally broadcast on 3FM in the Netherlands, his show gained success and is now played in the Netherlands (3FM), Belgium (Studio Brussels), Ireland (2FM) and Turkey (FG Istanbul). Also thanks to the success of White Noise he launched a new label White Noise too, where he ...

entry.title: The Coming Storm in the Middle East & N. Africa
entry.content: I've been looking into Halliburton for a little over a year, and about 3 months ago, I came across the General Wesley Clark interview. To say I was stunned and amazed would be an understatement. Recent news has given even more proof that this country lies to its citizens, military, and world allies about its reasoning for going to war. I have lost several friends in some of these wars that might be here today, if this were revealed to the world. My goal is to prevent anymore from that same fate. To die for your country is an honor, but when the wars are based on lies and deception, it taints that ultimate sacrafice, This deception is tied to many others both abroad and here at home. Research, share, discuss, and subscribe. Thank you to those who have viewed and shared this information. Enlightenment of the masses is my goal here. Other then the opinions given, I do not claim this material as my own, & the material used in this video is subject to the copyrights that apply. The music in this video; Johnny Cash "God's Gonna Cut you down"

entry.title: Danny Clark & Jay Benham Ft Dawn Tallman - Conqueror [Alix Alvarez Vocal Mix]
entry.content: URL to Buy: www.traxsource.com "This is the first release on the label and there are no holds barred as a stellar cast have been brought together for this project. Danny and Jay were the men behind last years aptly named Wondrous with Su Su Bobien, and fans of that release are set to be equally delighted with Conqueror. Dawn Tallman on vocals needs little or no introduction, having featured on some of the best known labels all over the world since her debut back in 1994. The package includes remixes from producers at the very top of their game in the shape of Alix Alvarez, Frankie Feliciano, Guy Robin, not to mention two further mixes from Jay and Danny. Every time I think Ive picked out a favourite mix, one of the other mixes grabs my attention again and Im back to square one. This is soulful house music of the very highest calibre and a wonderful way to get the label off the ground, (no pun intended)." Dean Serafini JJazproJect Magazine _______________________ "'Wondrous', Danny Clark & Jay Benham's debut as a production duo, took the dance floors by storm last year and has been a favourite with many DJ's to this day. Now they are about to launch their own label Solid Ground Recordings, and the first release on the label is nothing less than a masterpiece. On 'Conqueror', Danny & Jay team up with the one and only Dawn Tallman who contributes an outstanding heartfelt vocal on the funk-soaked, fierce yet smooth production that oozes with jazzy piano and marvellous organs ...

entry.title: First prediction of a recession in New Zealand
entry.content: www.interest.co.nz Intro Hello. I'm Bernard Hickey with the weekend edition of the daily briefing from interest.co.nz... Today, we'll look at the first prediction of a recession in New Zealand. The BNZ has made a gutsy call that we may already be in recession and we'll look at the latest productivity figures. They may sound boring but they unlock the secret of why New Zealand's economy is performing so badly. Story 1, But firstly, we look at a very gutsy call from an economist. The BNZ's Stephen Toplis has put it all on the line and come out with a prediction that the New Zealand economy is heading for a recession possibly as early as the third and fourth quarters of this year. That's just over 3 months away. The BNZ's Toplis says New Zealand's economy has become the victim of a near perfect storm of bad news. At the same time as the global credit crunch we have a housing market starting to slump, very high interest rates and a very high New Zealand dollar. We also have high petrol and food prices, which is putting disposable income under a lot of stress. He says interest rates for borrowers are likely to go higher because of the credit crunch and he sees the prospect of credit rationing by the banks. He is now predicting a double digit fall in house prices. He sees rents rising too as money for new developments dries up. An interesting view that will no doubt spark debate. You can do that on the ratesblog on interest.co.nz Story 2 Now for a closer look at productivity ...
